1
00:00:00,674 --> 00:00:15,164
Popeye the Sailor and the Belgian boy reporter Tintin lead the class of characters and works of art to enter public domain in 2025.

2
00:00:16,263 --> 00:00:25,937
On January 1, 2025, the U.S. copyright ends on creations from 1929.

3
00:00:26,017 --> 00:00:36,790
That means the early versions of the comic characters can be used without permission or payment.

4
00:00:38,010 --> 00:00:49,823
They will be joined by the books A Farewell to Arms by Ernest Hemingway and The Sound and the Fury by William Faulkner.

5
00:00:51,042 --> 00:01:15,381
Other works coming into the public domain include songs from American artist Cole Porter, early films from Alfred Hitchcock and the Marx Brothers, and several more films starring Mickey Mouse, whose earliest version became public domain last year.

6
00:01:16,521 --> 00:01:42,504
“It’s a trove! There are a dozen new Mickey cartoons — he speaks for the first time and dons the familiar white gloves,” said Jennifer Jenkins, director of the Center for the Study of the Public Domain, part of Duke University Law School in North Carolina.

7
00:01:43,783 --> 00:02:06,251
“There are masterpieces from Faulkner and Hemingway, the first sound films from Alfred Hitchcock, Cecil B. DeMille, and John Ford, and amazing music from Fats Waller, Cole Porter, and George Gershwin. Pretty exciting,” she added.

8
00:02:07,311 --> 00:02:16,008
Here is a closer look from the Associated Press at this year’s crop of public domain works:

9
00:02:17,268 --> 00:02:34,354
Popeye the Sailor, with his big arm muscles and fighting spirit, was created by E.C.Segar and made his first appearance in the newspaper comic strip Thimble Theater in 1929.

10
00:02:36,193 --> 00:02:42,968
His first words were, “’Ja think I’m a cowboy?” when asked if he was a sailor.

11
00:02:44,307 --> 00:02:48,624
It was supposed to be a one-time appearance for the character.

12
00:02:49,883 --> 00:02:56,682
Instead, he became the main character, and the strip would be renamed Popeye.

13
00:02:57,921 --> 00:03:08,414
But as with Mickey Mouse last year and Winnie the Pooh in 2022, only the earliest version is free for reuse.

14
00:03:10,073 --> 00:03:19,726
Popeye did not become a film character until 1933 and that version remains under copyright.

15
00:03:19,746 --> 00:03:32,325
The 1929 version of the character Tintin, the creation of Belgian artist Hergé, will also come into the public domain.

16
00:03:32,325 --> 00:03:48,519
The simply drawn teenager with dots for eyes and hair shaped like an ocean wave, was among the most popular characters in Europe for much of the 20th century.

17
00:03:49,698 --> 00:04:02,315
However, in much of the world, Tintin will not become public property until 70 years after the 1983 death of his creator.

18
00:04:03,734 --> 00:04:12,272
The books entering the public domain this year read like a list for an American literature class.

19
00:04:13,292 --> 00:04:20,010
The Sound and the Fury is arguably William Faulkner’s most famous book.

20
00:04:21,065 --> 00:04:33,222
Its special style of expression was a big hit although the book was widely considered difficult to read and understand.

21
00:04:34,182 --> 00:04:43,380
The story is set in the southern state of Mississippi, where Faulkner was born and lived most of his life.

22
00:04:44,559 --> 00:04:48,618
It tells about the ruin of a leading family there.

23
00:04:49,526 --> 00:04:58,882
And Ernest Hemingway’s A Farewell to Arms joins his earlier The Sun Also Rises in the public domain.

24
00:04:58,882 --> 00:05:06,839
The story about an ambulance driver is set in Italy during World War I.

25
00:05:07,898 --> 00:05:12,377
It was based in part on Hemingway’s real life.

26
00:05:13,416 --> 00:05:23,043
It has been made into film, TV, and radio versions, and now can be done anew without permission.

27
00:05:23,043 --> 00:05:32,037
American John Steinbeck’s first novel, A Cup of Gold, will also enter the public domain.

28
00:05:33,196 --> 00:05:40,731
Filmmaking was changing from silent to sound production during the late 1920s.

29
00:05:42,190 --> 00:05:50,656
The famous moviemaker Alfred Hitchcock was still living in Britain when he made the film Blackmail.

30
00:05:51,976 --> 00:06:00,471
The movie began as a silent film but was turned to sound film during production.

31
00:06:00,471 --> 00:06:03,249
Two versions of Blackmail were released.

32
00:06:04,329 --> 00:06:10,025
One of the versions became Britain’s and Hitchcock’s first sound film.

33
00:06:11,584 --> 00:06:19,816
American John Ford is probably best remembered for making the kind of films called Westerns.

34
00:06:21,075 --> 00:06:23,694
Those movies remain protected.

35
00:06:24,733 --> 00:06:34,728
But, Ford’s first sound film, 1929’s The Black Watch, enters the public domain next month.

36
00:06:36,167 --> 00:06:42,983
The action movie includes a young John Wayne who appears in a small part.

37
00:06:44,223 --> 00:06:48,840
Years later, Wayne was the star of many Ford films.

38
00:06:50,499 --> 00:07:04,449
Another notable director, Cecil B.DeMille, already a Hollywood leader in silent films, made Dynamite his first sound film in 1929.

39
00:07:06,048 --> 00:07:16,910
Groucho, Harpo, and the other Marx Brothers humor group had their first starring parts in 1929’s The Cocoanuts.

40
00:07:18,390 --> 00:07:25,309
The brothers went on to make the popular comedies, Animal Crackers and Duck Soup.

41
00:07:26,909 --> 00:07:33,967
And The Broadway Melody will also enter the public domain on January 1.

42
00:07:35,207 --> 00:07:47,397
It became the first sound film and the second film ever to win the Oscar for best picture — then called “outstanding production.”

43
00:07:48,636 --> 00:07:57,350
Songs from the last year of the 1920s are also about to become publicly available for use.

44
00:07:58,469 --> 00:08:18,001
Cole Porter’s compositions What Is This Thing Called Love? and Tiptoe Through the Tulips are among the highlights, as is the jazz classic Ain’t Misbehavin’ written by Fats Waller and Harry Brooks.

45
00:08:18,841 --> 00:08:21,881
Different laws cover sound recordings.

46
00:08:22,841 --> 00:08:28,320
Those newly in the public domain date to 1924.

47
00:08:29,100 --> 00:08:46,935
They include a recording of Nobody Knows the Trouble I’ve Seen from star and civil rights icon Marian Anderson, and Rhapsody in Blue performed by its composer George Gershwin.

48
00:08:48,312 --> 00:08:51,586
I’m Caty Weaver.

49
00:08:51,586 --> 00:08:53,586
And I’m Dorothy Gundy.
